% You are an expert prompt writer and MCP architect for PDD MCP Server. Your goal is to produce a high-quality prompt that, when passed to `pdd generate`, will produce the associated Python file for the {module} in the MCP Server.

% Here is the README.md for the MCP Server that will be created from the CSV file: <readme><include>README.md</include></readme>

% Here is the Readme.md for the PDD CLI: <pdd_readme><include>../README.md</include></pdd_readme>

% Here is the MCP documentation: <mcp_docs><web>https://modelcontextprotocol.io/llms-full.txt</web></mcp_docs>

% Here is a csv file containing the description, input and outputs for the function and the dependencies for the backend Python files for the project: <file_dependencies><include>prompts/io_dependencies.csv</include></file_dependencies>

% Here is the CLI version of the generate code prompt to use as a reference: <generate_code_cli_example><include>../../prompts/code_generator_python.prompt</include></generate_code_cli_example>

% Here are the prompt files generated so far for the backend Python files to use as reference:
<python_files>
    <shell>find prompts -name "*_python.prompt" -type f | while read file; do
    echo "File: $file"
    cat "$file"
    echo
    echo  "****************************************************************"
    echo # Add a new line for spacing
done</shell>
</python_files>

% Do the following:
 - Analyze the {module} MCP tool's responsibilities from the README, the io_dependencies CSV, and the existing backend prompts
 - Identify any difficulties the downstream code generation might encounter (e.g. MCP protocol compliance, tool-schema validation, stdio transport edge cases, async contract mismatches) and state mitigation strategies tailored to the MCP Server stack
 - Place the direct code-generation instruction for {module} inside xml tags called prompt. The content inside `<prompt>...</prompt>` must instruct the code-generating LLM to produce the Python implementation - it must NOT instruct the LLM to produce further prompt text about the module.
    - Any dependencies that are needed for this prompt will have the filepath in between two include angle bracket xml tags, surrounded by xml tags [dependency_name]_example. The dependencies will be in the context folder so you can assume the filepath will be context/[dependency_name]_example.py.
